title: Part 4
content:
Part 4

FROM THE SURROUNDING clamor, Class C and D soon learned that an intense firefight had begun. At the same time, the commanders reported that Class A likely used a tactic, along with who'd been taken out. Eight from Class B and five from Class A. Perhaps as a result of getting the drop on them from behind, a slight advantage had begun to emerge in that short amount of time.

"Looks like Class A circled around back and engaged Class B."

"Yeah... If we keep advancing now, we can trap Class B between us—"

"But you get it, right, Kanzaki? The orders we got from Ayanokouji were..."

"I understand."

Nodding, Kanzaki immediately ran to the rear. He then began to move out with the members he'd spoken to in advance. After seeing them off, he turned his attention back to the front.

"It's been about five minutes since the shooting started, right? For all that, maybe not as many people have been taken out as I thought."

When he murmured, speaking to Takemoto, who walked beside him, Takemoto also nodded in agreement.

"Doesn't that just mean they're fighting while prioritizing defense?"

"Well then, shall we get going—"

Just as he rose from his crouch, a paintball hit the shoulder of Matoba, who'd been preparing beside Hashimoto.

"Hgh!?"

His watch announced that he was out and Hashimoto, judging it was dangerous to stay there, immediately fled.

"It's Class A! Hirata's here, Hashimoto!"

Matoba, who'd been shot, shouted as he glared in the direction the paintball came from.

"Hirata? Didn't he circle around behind Class B...!"

There, Hashimoto understood that it wasn't their entire class, but that Class A sent only some of their students around back, leaving several behind to deal with the alliance.

"Take us out with a small group? Are they serious?"

At that point, Class A had 16 to 19 guards remaining. Assuming they assigned half of them to Class B, it wasn't realistic for the remaining eight or nine to take on an allied class of about 40 people. The number of paintballs that occasionally flew their way was by no means large.

Even when they shot back, there wasn't an overwhelming retaliatory volley.

"...What's going on...?"

Hashimoto thought they split into two groups, but they might have actually been divided into even smaller units.

The advance had initially begun with the intention of pressing Class A with Class B and the allied classes to drop them to last place. However, Class A's use of tactics shut down the overall GPS and part of Class A circled around behind Class B. Meanwhile, the allied classes continued to advance, figuring it didn't matter if the target they were trapping switched from Class A to Class B, but the ones they were actually facing were from Class A.

Just then, a faint shout could be heard from the direction Kanzaki went, the complete opposite of where Hirata's group was hiding.

"Damn, what the hell... I can't even tell who's fighting where anymore...!"

With the VIP no longer nearby, he had no way of grasping the details of the battlefield. That being the case, he cleared his head for a moment. The only thing Hashimoto could do was to confront Hirata and the other Class A students and win.

But that was difficult. Hashimoto attacked, using his paintballs without hesitation, but they kept changing their positions and he couldn't get a clear shot.

What's more, the paintballs they shot back always grazed just past Hashimoto.

"Not bad, Hirata... You're way more skilled than I thought. There's no hesitation or mercy in your aim."

Hashimoto broke out in a cold sweat, letting slip his frank impression of Hirata, who was hiding up ahead.

He knew from the start that Hirata was good at sports, but his miscalculation lay elsewhere.

The naked killing intent, unbecoming of a mere honor student, was what surprised Hashimoto more than anything.

Even if it meant a mutual takedown, he would absolutely defeat his opponent.

Even that level of intent seemed to be flying toward Hashimoto along with the paintballs.

"—Hah..."

While confronting his rising heart rate, Hashimoto racked his brain for a way out of the situation.

Judging by the back-and-forth so far, Hirata had slightly more momentum, but their skills were evenly matched.

The number of rounds left in his magazine was less than half and it was entirely possible that Hirata had a spare.

Even if he tried to use the terrain to flank him, it wouldn't be easy, given who his opponent was.

"...No matter how you look at it, I'm at a disadvantage, huh."

If that was the case, should he settle for a mutual takedown? No, that conclusion could wait a little longer.

The only area where he could confidently say he had the upper hand was with his words.

It wasn't too late to use them.

Since his position was exposed anyway, there was no problem with raising his voice.

"Never seen you with such a desperate look on your face before! Did getting abandoned by Ayanokouji really piss you off that much?!"

It was a taunt meant to agitate him, thinking it would be a win if it made his aiming hand waver.

The loud voice that echoed through the forest was soon swallowed and silence returned.

"How 'bout it? I could ask Ayanokouji to negotiate pulling you into our class. You're a sharp guy and the girls love you. I bet we could get you a seat at the table, eh?"

He considered psychological warfare to be the key to victory and thoroughly tried to rattle him.

Hashimoto thought that if Hirata responded skillfully, he'd have him right where he wanted him.

However, even as time passed, Hirata still didn't respond.

"Givin' me the silent treatment, huh? You could at least say some—"

Just as he was about to call out again, a sound of rustling through the bushes came from the direction where Hirata was likely hiding.

"Tch...!"

It was Hirata who moved first. But Hashimoto's reaction wasn't delayed. Conscious of their remaining ammunition, they read each other's lines of fire. Firing using tree trunks for cover, sliding with their bodies half-turned, a series of short feints canceled out each other's aim. The bullets flew in high, thin arcs.

"Whoa, that was close!"

Just after Hashimoto pulled his face back behind the tree, the paintball hit the trunk and splattered spectacularly.

The rise in tension was extraordinary, as a direct hit meant instant elimination.

The series of exchanges at a relatively close range was a rapid succession of impacts. Bullets grazed the tree bark and pulverized the fallen leaves on the ground. Hashimoto spun his body at a sharp angle, trying to get to Hirata's flank, but Hirata had read his move. Lowering his stance, a single shot returned from the hip grazed Hashimoto's shoulder, leaving a stain.

"Kuh...!"

A cry of anguish, not of pain. The trivial mistake born from losing the exchange of wits sent a chill down his spine.

"And I don't have time to be wasting on one guy..."

He held his weapon vertically and tried to recall the times he pulled the trigger during the fight, wondering how many rounds he had left.

He had certainly fired more than forty shots, leaving only a few at best.

Should he change the magazine early, or should he use up every last shot?

His opponent showed no sign of reloading either and likely had a similar number of rounds left.

Both were close to emptying their magazines, hinting at the need to reload. The existence of spare magazines dulled the choice between offense and defense. To retreat meant defeat. To push through meant victory. But half the battle was a dialogue of the mind—in other words, psychological warfare. Every piece of information, from each other's breathing and the trembling of their fingers to their habits of shifting weight on the soles of their shoes, was crucial. For a moment, Hashimoto hid in the shade of a tree before trying a ploy in a low voice.

"Ayanokouji was sayin' he felt bad about what he did to you, Hirata."

As his voice broke the forest's silence like a rolling pebble, Hirata's gaze faltered for just an instant at those words.

Betting on that slight mental disturbance, Hashimoto leaped out. He squeezed the trigger with all his might.

He certainly caught Hirata by surprise. But—although two bullets flew out, they missed and unluckily, a third failed to emerge. He was out of ammo.

Hirata immediately composed himself for a counterattack and pulled the trigger in return.

Near Hashimoto's ear, bang!, paint splattered and color spread across the edge of his goggle's field of view.

His vision was obstructed. That was a huge disadvantage.

He dove back behind the tree and immediately kicked off the ground.

His vision reduced to about thirty percent, Hashimoto immediately chose to create distance. He had to move quickly between the trees and regroup. Hirata could've shot Hashimoto in the back, but he too ran out of ammo at that exact moment. He pursued him, determined not to let him escape. They changed locations, once again bringing themselves to a close-range standoff.

It was a tense situation where the match would be decided in an instant if either of them showed the slightest opening.

With no time to worry about appearances, Hashimoto slid his goggles onto his forehead, removed the assault rifle's magazine and immediately swapped it with his spare.

He then desperately rubbed the stained goggles with his fingertips to get the paint off, but seeing no significant improvement, he had no choice but to slide them back over his eyes.

"So this is what they call a desperate situation...!"

Hashimoto still had fifty rounds left. But when they ran out, it would be over.

On the other hand, Hashimoto didn't know how many rounds Hirata had.

Of course, the same was true for Hirata. He didn't know how many rounds his opponent had.

There was even a possibility that he had no spare magazine and had just fired his last shot.

In that case, should he risk it and close the distance before Hirata could escape?

In a battle of attrition, mental fatigue would set in before physical exhaustion. Should he aim for a quick, decisive battle, or try to bait a mistake from his opponent in a war of attrition? Their breaths overlapped as the pale afternoon light streamed into the forest.

Who would be the first to make a fatal misstep?

Breathing heavily, Hashimoto peeked the muzzle of his gun just slightly from behind the tree.

Sweat dripped from his chin. He saw Hirata's shadow move at the edge of his vision.

It was now or never.

Hashimoto took aim and leaped out at once, closing the distance to Hirata.

Immediately after, a dual gunshot rang out.

The paintballs whizzed past each other and a sound like the air itself was splitting echoed through the forest.

"...!"

Hashimoto felt a hot sensation on his chest. Lowering his gaze, he saw the paint that had hit him slowly spreading.

Hirata's shot, fired at almost the same time, had been slightly faster.

The elimination tone sounded.

It should have been a lifeless electronic sound, but strangely, it sent a chill deep into his body.

"Damn it—!"

The shock sent Hashimoto to one knee.

His breathing was ragged and his throat was parched as if it were on fire.

The match was decided—he understood that logically, but his heart hadn't accepted the end.

"...That was some serious spirit, Hirata. This match is my loss."

He praised Hirata in a hoarse voice.

It was a defeat that came after fighting with all his might.

Hirata didn't answer, he simply lowered his gun slowly.

The movement stopped after a brief pause.

His gaze, fixed on the kneeling Hashimoto, didn't move.

The muzzle of the gun slowly rose once more.

"Hey... Hirata...?"

Hashimoto's breath caught as he looked into Hirata's eyes.

He could see a finger being placed on the trigger.

Hashimoto was already out and the match had been completely decided.

If he were to add a follow-up attack, a heavy penalty awaited Class A.

"If this is a joke, I'm not laughing."

The muzzle was pressed against his forehead. It was truly point-blank range.

A position from which he might be seriously injured if the trigger were pulled.

He might get shot.

Just as that impossible delusion crossed his mind, the trigger—was squeezed partway and then Hirata's finger stopped moving.

Silence fell.

The wind passed through the forest. The smell of paint mixed with the dampness of the earth.

Hirata said nothing, lowered the gun and turned his back.

The students of Class A and Class C were still fighting in a different area and he had to go support them.

In the ears of Hashimoto who was left behind, an echo lingered as if he could hear the unsqueezed trigger and a gunshot.

"Guess I pushed the honor student a little too far—"

It was a sharp fear, no different from actually having been shot a second time.
